\subsection*{Question 1} {\bf [Hatcher 2.2.9 (a), and (b)]}
\\ \noindent Compute the homology groups of the following 2-complexes:
\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
\item The quotient of $S^2$ obtained by identifying north and south
  poles to a point.
\item $S^1\times (S^1\vee S^1)$.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{proof}
  {\bf (a)} We can identify the quotient of $S^2$ that identifies the
  north and south poles with the quotient space made by collapsing a
  subspace $A=S^1\times \{a\}\subset T$ to a point, where $T$ is the
  torus and $a$ is some point in $S^1$. Observe that $(T, A)$ is an
  NDR-pair, since we can choose some small $\varepsilon$ such that the
  open set $S^1\times[a-\varepsilon, a+\varepsilon]$ deformation
  retracts onto $A$. Thus, the quotient map $q$ induces an isomorphism
  $H_n(T,A)\cong \tilde{H}_n(T/A)$. This allows us to compute the
  homology groups of $T/A$ via the LES of a pair.  (I guess I should
  tikz this at least once...)
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}
      0 \rar& H_2(A) \rar & H_2(T) \rar & H_2(T,A) \ar[out=-20, in=160]{dll} \\
      & H_1(A) \rar & H_1(T) \rar & H_1(T,A) \ar[out=-20, in=160]{dll} \\
      & H_0(A) \rar & H_0(T) \rar & H_0(T,A) \rar & 0.
    \end{tikzcd}
  \end{center}
  Using the fact $A\simeq S^1$, and our computations of the homology
  groups of spheres and the torus, we can fill in our LES.
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tikzcd}
      0 \rar& 0 \rar & \bbZ \rar & H_2(T,A) \ar[out=-20, in=160, "(1)"']{dll} \\
      & \bbZ \arrow[r, "(2)"] & \bbZ\{a,b\} \arrow[r, "(3)"] &
      H_1(T,A)
      \ar[out=-20, in=160, "(4)"']{dll} \\
      & \bbZ \arrow[r, "(5)"] & \bbZ \arrow[r, "(6)"] & H_0(T,A) \rar
      & 0.
    \end{tikzcd}
  \end{center}
  First observe that the map $(2)$ sends the generator of $\bbZ$ to
  the the generator $a$ where $a$ is the meridian of the torus. In
  particular the kernel of $(2)$ is trivial, and thus the map $(1)$ is
  the zero map. Hence $H_2(T,A)\cong \bbZ$. Furthermore, the kernel of
  $(3)$ must be $\bbZ\{a\}$, hence $\im(3) = \bbZ \subset H_1(T,A)$.
  By considering the connected components of $A$ and $T$, we see that
  $(5)$ is an isomorphism, i.e. it sends 1 to $\pm 1$, hence $(4)$ and
  $(6)$ are both the zero maps. Thus we can conclude that
  $H_1(T,A)\cong \im(3) = \bbZ$ and $H_0(T,A) = 0$.

  Finally, we use the fact that, for a general space $X$,
  \[ H_i(X) \cong
    \begin{cases}
      \widetilde{H}_i(X) & i>0,\\
      \widetilde{H}_i(X)\oplus \bbZ & i = 0
    \end{cases}
  \]
  to conclude that
  \[ H_i(T/A) \cong
    \begin{cases}
      \bbZ & i=0,1,2,\\
      0 & i > 2.
    \end{cases}
  \]
  \\
  \\
  \noindent
  {\bf (b)} Next we consider the space $X= S^1 \times(S^1\vee
  S^1)$. This space is homotopy equivalent to the space that is two
  2-tori stacked on top of one another, i.e. glued along their
  longitudinal circle.
\end{proof}

